@Tim

I have encountered this word in these puzzles before. I was like you then: What the actual fotchke!?

And this even though Polish has an etymologically linked word, but one which we spell completely differently: cacko.

@Andrzej

“What the actual fotchke!?”

Oww, coffee hurts coming out through the nose…

@Tim

TCHOTCHKE has its unusual spelling, I think, because it derives from Yiddish, in which (via transliteration), the digraph ch usually refers to the guttural sound found in Chanukah, Pesach, l'chaim, and, non-Yiddishly, Bach or loch.

The "tch's" are like the "ch" in (ironically) "church."

@Times Rita
I once had to send out an email flyer about the Festival of Lights. I spelled it differently each time it appeared. Six times. Heh.

 They're all just attempts at transliteration; I'm not sure any one is 'right'.

@Sam Lyons

I keep looking at dictionary definitions and I just don't see that. Or am I wrong? I probably am, given it is you commenting on language, and I know no better person to do that 😃. However, syntetyczny is a word in Polish, and for us it may never mean fake, forged, inauthentic or ersatz. It only ever means artificial (as in, plastic fibers vs cotton), distilled (metaphorically speaking) or intelligently brief.

Ultimately it may be that the clue is only utterly unacceptable to me because I'm Polish, and even though I'm interpreting synthetic as syntetyczny, the meanings of both words ale slightly different.

@Sam Lyons

Maybe my head is broken but I don't see how these definitions leading to synthetic being equal to fake... Possibly this is a level of language understanding and intuition that's beyond a non-native speaker. And then there is my Polish baggage, with essentially the same word not meaning forged...

I appreciate your explaining this to me. Maybe I'm just too thick to get it.

@Bruce

That doesn't quite work for me. I would call it fake but I wouldn't call it synthetic - and definitely not in Polish. I might consider calling a robot's smile synthetic, I guess - that would be a case of artificiality that falls under my understanding of being synthetic.

Btw, do fake smiles work on people? They immediately put me off. When I was buying one of our cars, the guy at the dealership tried all his tricks on me initially, fake smile and all, but when he realized none of it worked he just became a normal person 🤣 - and then I could finally talk to him about getting a car.

